        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Is Cognee?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cognee is an open-source memory framework that builds a queryable knowledge graph from heterogeneous data sources \u2014 plain text, URLs, PDFs, code repositories, and structured data \u2014 using a two-step pipeline: add() stages raw data, and cognify() runs entity extraction, relationship inference, embedding, and graph construction. The result is a unified knowledge store that can be queried with four distinct search types: raw chunk retrieval, graph-aware insights, LLM-generated summaries, and graph-completion answers. All backends (graph, vector, relational) are pluggable \u2014 the default stack (NetworkX + LanceDB + SQLite) requires no external services."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Cognee data pipeline architecture",
          "title": ""
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Setup and Configuration"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cognee reads LLM and vector store configuration from environment variables (OPENAI_API_KEY, etc.) or from explicit config calls. The default backend stack (LanceDB + NetworkX + SQLite) requires no external services and is ideal for development. Switch to Neo4j + Qdrant + Postgres for production deployments."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Install: pip install cognee\n# Cognee uses LanceDB + NetworkX by default (no external services required).\n# Configure LLM and embedder via environment variables or the config API.\n\nimport cognee\nimport asyncio\n\nasync def setup():\n    # Configure LLM (defaults to OpenAI if OPENAI_API_KEY is set)\n    cognee.config.set_llm_config({\n        \"llm_api_key\": \"your-openai-api-key\",\n        \"llm_model\": \"gpt-4o-mini\",\n        \"llm_provider\": \"openai\",\n    })\n\n    # Configure embedder\n    cognee.config.set_vectordb_config({\n        \"vector_db_provider\": \"lancedb\",   # or \"qdrant\", \"pgvector\"\n    })\n\n    # Optional: switch graph backend to Neo4j\n    # cognee.config.set_graph_database_provider(\"neo4j\")\n\n    # Reset (clear all stored data) \u2014 use only in development\n    await cognee.prune.prune_data()\n    await cognee.prune.prune_system(metadata=True)\n\nasyncio.run(setup())\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "add() and cognify()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "add() accepts a string, Path, or URL and stages it for processing. cognify() runs the full pipeline on everything staged: chunking, entity and relationship extraction via LLM, embedding each chunk, and storing the results in the graph, vector, and relational backends. Cognify can take 10\u201360 seconds depending on data volume \u2014 run it once at session startup or after a batch of new documents, not on every agent turn."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Step 1: add() stages raw data into a dataset (no processing yet).\n# Step 2: cognify() runs the full pipeline: chunk, extract, embed, store.\n\nimport cognee\nimport asyncio\n\nasync def ingest():\n    # Add text directly\n    await cognee.add(\"Alice is the tech lead. The project uses FastAPI on Python 3.12.\")\n\n    # Add a URL (Cognee fetches and parses the page)\n    await cognee.add(\"https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/\", dataset_name=\"docs\")\n\n    # Add a local file\n    from pathlib import Path\n    await cognee.add(Path(\"architecture.md\"), dataset_name=\"project_docs\")\n\n    # cognify() processes everything staged with add() in the default dataset\n    # and all named datasets. This can take 10-60s depending on data volume.\n    await cognee.cognify()\n    print(\"Knowledge graph built.\")\n\nasyncio.run(ingest())\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Searching with SearchType"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "cognee.search() dispatches to different retrieval strategies based on SearchType. CHUNKS is the fastest \u2014 pure vector similarity over stored text chunks. INSIGHTS traverses the knowledge graph to surface entity relationships relevant to the query. SUMMARIES returns LLM-generated summaries of the most relevant graph nodes. GRAPH_COMPLETION uses the graph as grounding to generate a full LLM answer."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# cognee.search() queries the knowledge graph using different search types.\n# INSIGHTS   \u2014 graph-aware: returns entity relationships and derived facts\n# CHUNKS     \u2014 vector similarity: returns raw text chunks\n# SUMMARIES  \u2014 returns LLM-generated summaries of relevant nodes\n# GRAPH_COMPLETION \u2014 uses the graph to complete the answer with the LLM\n\nimport cognee\nimport asyncio\nfrom cognee.api.v1.search import SearchType\n\nasync def query():\n    # Graph-aware insights: traverses the knowledge graph\n    insights = await cognee.search(\n        \"who is the tech lead and what stack do they use?\",\n        search_type=SearchType.INSIGHTS,\n    )\n    print(\"=== INSIGHTS ===\")\n    for item in insights:\n        print(item)\n\n    # Raw chunk retrieval: pure vector similarity, like a standard RAG search\n    chunks = await cognee.search(\n        \"FastAPI Python version\",\n        search_type=SearchType.CHUNKS,\n    )\n    print(\"\\n=== CHUNKS ===\")\n    for chunk in chunks:\n        print(chunk)\n\n    # Graph completion: LLM answers the question grounded in graph data\n    answer = await cognee.search(\n        \"What framework and language does the project use?\",\n        search_type=SearchType.GRAPH_COMPLETION,\n    )\n    print(\"\\n=== GRAPH_COMPLETION ===\")\n    print(answer)\n\nasyncio.run(query())\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Dataset Scoping for Multi-User Deployments"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pass dataset_name to add() and datasets=[...] to cognify() and search() to isolate data by user, project, or session. Datasets are logical partitions \u2014 they share the same backends but queries are filtered to the specified dataset only. This is the standard approach for multi-tenant deployments where each user's knowledge must not bleed into another's."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Datasets let you scope add/cognify/search to a named partition.\n# This supports multi-user or multi-project deployments within one Cognee instance.\n\nimport cognee\nimport asyncio\nfrom cognee.api.v1.search import SearchType\n\nasync def multi_dataset():\n    # Ingest into separate named datasets\n    await cognee.add(\n        \"Alice manages the backend team. Bob owns the frontend.\",\n        dataset_name=\"team_context\",\n    )\n    await cognee.add(\n        \"Q3 revenue target is $2M. Current run-rate is $1.6M.\",\n        dataset_name=\"finance_context\",\n    )\n\n    # Process only a specific dataset\n    await cognee.cognify(datasets=[\"team_context\"])\n    await cognee.cognify(datasets=[\"finance_context\"])\n\n    # Search within a specific dataset\n    results = await cognee.search(\n        \"who manages backend?\",\n        search_type=SearchType.INSIGHTS,\n        datasets=[\"team_context\"],  # restrict to team_context only\n    )\n    for r in results:\n        print(r)\n\nasyncio.run(multi_dataset())\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Agent Integration Pattern"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A typical agent pattern: call build_session_memory() at session start to ingest the relevant documents into a named dataset, then call cognee.search(INSIGHTS) before each LLM call to retrieve graph-grounded context. Inject the results into the system prompt. This gives the agent entity-aware memory without requiring it to manage vector queries directly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Integrating Cognee into an agent: cognify once on session start,\n# then call search(INSIGHTS) before each LLM turn to retrieve\n# graph-grounded context.\n\nimport cognee\nimport asyncio\nfrom cognee.api.v1.search import SearchType\nfrom openai import AsyncOpenAI\n\noai = AsyncOpenAI(api_key=\"...\")\n\nasync def build_session_memory(session_docs: list[str], session_id: str):\n    \"\"\"Ingest session documents into a named dataset.\"\"\"\n    for doc in session_docs:\n        await cognee.add(doc, dataset_name=session_id)\n    await cognee.cognify(datasets=[session_id])\n\nasync def agent_turn(user_input: str, session_id: str) -> str:\n    # Retrieve graph-grounded insights relevant to the user query\n    insights = await cognee.search(\n        user_input,\n        search_type=SearchType.INSIGHTS,\n        datasets=[session_id],\n    )\n    ctx_lines = [str(item) for item in insights[:6]]\n    memory_block = \"\\n\".join(ctx_lines) if ctx_lines else \"(no relevant memory)\"\n\n    messages = [\n        {\"role\": \"system\",\n         \"content\": f\"You are a helpful assistant.\\n\\nKnowledge context:\\n{memory_block}\"},\n        {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_input},\n    ]\n    resp = await oai.chat.completions.create(model=\"gpt-4o-mini\", messages=messages)\n    return resp.choices[0].message.content\n\nasync def main():\n    await build_session_memory(\n        [\"Alice is tech lead.\", \"The stack is FastAPI + Postgres 16.\"],\n        session_id=\"sess_001\",\n    )\n    reply = await agent_turn(\"Who leads the team and what database do they use?\", \"sess_001\")\n    print(reply)\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common Pitfalls"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "cognify() is not incremental by default",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2014 Calling cognify() a second time without pruning re-processes everything staged with add(). For incremental updates, use dataset scoping and call cognify(datasets=[new_dataset]) on only the new data."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "LanceDB default is in-process",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2014 The default LanceDB store writes to a local directory. In multi-process or containerised deployments, all processes must share the same filesystem path or switch to an external vector store (Qdrant, pgvector)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "GRAPH_COMPLETION is slower than CHUNKS",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2014 GRAPH_COMPLETION makes additional LLM calls to synthesise an answer from graph data. Use CHUNKS for latency-sensitive retrieval and GRAPH_COMPLETION only when the question requires cross-entity reasoning."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "prune_data() is destructive",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2014 await cognee.prune.prune_data() deletes all stored knowledge. Never call it in production \u2014 it is a development reset utility."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Custom Cognify Pipelines"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The cognify() pipeline is a list of task functions. You can replace or augment individual steps \u2014 for example, inserting a summarisation step before graph extraction to reduce noise in long documents, or replacing the default entity extractor with a domain-specific one. Import the built-in tasks from cognee.tasks and compose them with run_tasks()."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Cognee pipelines are composable \u2014 you can add or replace processing steps.\n# A pipeline is a list of tasks; each task receives the output of the previous one.\n\nimport cognee\nimport asyncio\nfrom cognee.tasks.summarization import summarize_text\nfrom cognee.tasks.graph import extract_graph_from_data\nfrom cognee.tasks.storage import store_data_to_graph\nfrom cognee.api.v1.cognify.cognify_v2 import run_tasks\n\nasync def custom_cognify():\n    # Stage your data first\n    await cognee.add('Alice approved the FastAPI migration on Nov 3.')\n\n    # Build a custom pipeline: summarize \u2192 extract graph \u2192 store\n    pipeline = [\n        summarize_text,           # LLM summarises each chunk first\n        extract_graph_from_data,  # extract entities and relations\n        store_data_to_graph,      # write to graph + vector store\n    ]\n\n    # Run the custom pipeline on the default dataset\n    await run_tasks(pipeline, dataset_name='default')\n    print('Custom pipeline complete.')\n\nasyncio.run(custom_cognify())\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Inspecting the Knowledge Graph"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Access the underlying graph store directly via get_graph_db() to enumerate all extracted nodes and edges. This is useful during development to verify that cognify() extracted the expected entities and relationships. The NetworkX graph export lets you visualise the knowledge graph or run graph algorithms (centrality, community detection) outside Cognee."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Export the knowledge graph for inspection or external tooling.\n# Cognee exposes the underlying NetworkX graph via the graph store API.\n\nimport cognee\nimport asyncio\nfrom cognee.infrastructure.databases.graph import get_graph_db\n\nasync def inspect_graph():\n    graph_db = get_graph_db()\n\n    # Get all nodes with their attributes\n    nodes = await graph_db.get_all_graph_nodes()\n    print(f'Total nodes: {len(nodes)}')\n    for node in nodes[:5]:\n        print(f'  [{node[\"type\"]}] {node[\"name\"]} (id={node[\"id\"][:8]}...)')\n\n    # Get all edges (relationships)\n    edges = await graph_db.get_all_graph_edges()\n    print(f'Total edges: {len(edges)}')\n    for edge in edges[:5]:\n        print(f'  {edge[\"source_name\"]} --[{edge[\"relationship_name\"]}]--> {edge[\"target_name\"]}')\n\n    # Export as a NetworkX graph for visualisation or further analysis\n    nx_graph = await graph_db.get_graph()\n    print(f'NetworkX: {nx_graph.number_of_nodes()} nodes, {nx_graph.number_of_edges()} edges')\n    # nx.draw(nx_graph) or export with nx.node_link_data(nx_graph)\n\nasyncio.run(inspect_graph())\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cognee vs Graphiti, Mem0, and Zep"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "All four frameworks build a knowledge store from unstructured text, but they differ in ingestion model, search capabilities, and scoping mechanism."
          }
        ]
      },
